from matplotlib.colors import LinearSegmentedColormap

n, bins, patches = plt.hist(df['Age'], bins=20, edgecolor='white', alpha= 0.8)
plt.title('Age Distribution', color='Black')
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('frequency')


cmap = LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list('shades_of_cyan', ['cyan','red'])
norm = plt.Normalize(vmin=n.min(), vmax=n.max())

for bin_value, patch in zip(n, patches):
    color = cmap(norm(bin_value))
    patch.set_facecolor(color)

  1. Statiscial Analysis
In [ ]:
#correlation analysis
correlation = df.corr()

plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
sns.heatmap(correlation, annot= True, cmap='BuPu', vmin=-1, vmax=1)
Out[ ]:
<Axes: >

There is a strong negative correlation between the Fare price and the Passenger Class, which is just misleading, since the upper class are notated with numerical values as 1, as first class. Obviously the first class tickets are more expensive than a lower passenger class such as 2 and 3.

There is also a strong positive correlation between the number of siblings and spouse, in the SibSp column and the Parch column which stands for the number of parents or guardians present. There was a higher number of Parch as the number of SibSp increases.

And there is a strong positive correlation of passengers survived and the fare price payed. Meaning that more people in higher passenger classes survived than people and lower passenger classes.

y = df['Fare']

model.fit(X, y)

predictions = model.predict(X)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

plt.plot(df['Age'], predictions, color='c', label='regression line')
plt.title('Fare vs Age Regression', color='Black')
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Fare')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

  1. Logistic regression
In [ ]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, confusion_matrix, classification_report, roc_curve, auc


#Data

x = df[['Fare']]  
y = df['Survived']  

#Model

mod = LogisticRegression()
mod.fit(x, y)
fare_pred = mod.predict(x)

#Metrics

accuracy = accuracy_score(y, fare_pred)
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y, fare_pred)
#class_report = classification_report(y, fare_pred)
df['Predicted_Probability'] = mod.predict_proba(x)[:, 1]
coef= mod.coef_[0][0]

#Print

print(f'Accuracy: {accuracy}')
print(f'Confusion Matrix:')
print(conf_matrix)
#print(class_report)
#print(df['Predicted_Probability'][: -1])
print(f'Coefficient: {coef}')

proba_table_high_p = df[['Fare', 'Predicted_Probability']].sort_values( by = 'Predicted_Probability', ascending= False)
proba_table_low_p = df[df['Fare'] > 0.000][['Fare', 'Predicted_Probability']].sort_values(by='Predicted_Probability', ascending=True)

proba_table_high_p_10 = proba_table_high_p.head(10)
proba_table_low_p_10 = proba_table_low_p.head(10)

print(f'High probability of survial :') 
print(proba_table_high_p_10)
print(f'Low probability of survival :')
print(proba_table_low_p_10)

#Visual

plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
sns.regplot(x='Fare', y='Predicted_Probability', data=df, logistic=True, ci=None, scatter_kws={'color': 'm'}, line_kws={'color': 'c'})
plt.title('Logistic Regression: Probability of Survival vs. Fare')
plt.xlabel('Fare')
plt.ylabel('Probability of Survival')
plt.show()

In [ ]:
fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y, df['Predicted_Probability'])
roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)


print(f'ROC AUC: {roc_auc}')


plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='c', lw=2, label=f'ROC curve (area = {roc_auc:.2f})')
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='m', linestyle='--')
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC)')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

ROC AUC: 0.6921223063730972

AUC = 1.0: Perfect model. AUC = 0.5: Model performs no better than random guessing. AUC < 0.5: Model performs worse than random guessing.
